  "observations": "# Observations\n\n## Brief/Code Discrepancies\n\n### No `writ-post` tool exists\nThe brief references a `writ-post` tool as a distinct integration point. This tool does not exist in the codebase. The only writ-creation tool is `commission-post`. The brief's three integration points (commission-post CLI, writ-post tool, writ-edit tool) collapse to two tool-level surfaces: `commission-post` and `writ-edit`. The spec should treat `commission-post` as covering both the CLI and tool-callable creation paths.\n\n### No CLI command file for commission-post\nThe brief references `packages/framework/cli/src/commands/commission-post.ts`. This file does not exist. The CLI dynamically generates Commander subcommands from plugin tool definitions via `buildToolCommand()` in `program.ts`. There is no per-tool CLI file to modify. The --strict flag must be added to the tool's Zod params, not to a CLI command file.\n\n### D20 references non-existent scope S8\nD20 was written with scope `[\\\"S8\\\", \\\"S2\\\"]` — S8 does not exist. This should be corrected to `[\\\"S1\\\", \\\"S2\\\"]` as the scanner function name relates to both the scanner module (S1) and its integration (S2).\n\n## Refactoring Opportunities\n\n### Tool handler has no caller context\nThe `ToolDefinition.handler` signature receives only validated params — no caller identity, no request metadata. This means there's no way for a handler to distinguish patron vs. anima calls. The current workaround (scanning in the tool handler = patron boundary) works because agents use `ClerkApi` directly, but it's fragile — if an agent ever calls tools through the Instrumentarium rather than the API, it would be scanned. A future commission could add an optional `context` parameter to the handler signature with caller metadata.\n\n### HTTP tool server returns 500 for application errors\nIn `tool-server.ts`, all non-Zod errors from tool handlers produce HTTP 500. A thrown injection-block error is an application-level rejection, not a server error. A future improvement could distinguish application errors (4xx) from unexpected failures (5xx), e.g., by checking for specific error types or a status code property on the Error.\n\n### ClerkApi.edit() request type inconsistency\n`EditWritRequest` requires `id` as a field, while `PostCommissionRequest` doesn't include an `id` (it's generated internally). When adding `injectionScan` to both request types, the field semantics differ slightly — on post, it's always a fresh scan; on edit, it replaces whatever was there. This isn't a bug but is worth noting for the spec writer.\n\n## Conventions Followed for Consistency\n\n### console.warn for non-error output\nThe codebase uses `console.warn()` for non-fatal warnings (see `clerk.ts` kit registration warnings at lines 141, 154, and `program.ts` guild load failure at line 179). Using `console.warn()` for injection match warnings in tool handlers follows this established pattern, even though a structured logging system would be better.\n\n### Test runner is native Node.js\nAll tests use `node:test` + `node:assert/strict`. No third-party test framework (jest, vitest, etc.). The scanner tests and integration tests must follow this convention. The test glob pattern is `src/**/*.test.ts`.\n\n## Potential Risks\n\n### Regex performance on adversarial input\nThe brief requires <10ms for 10kB body. Standard regex patterns should easily meet this, but pathological regex (catastrophic backtracking) on adversarial input could violate the constraint. The spec should require patterns to be tested against adversarial strings (e.g., long repeated characters that could trigger backtracking). Using non-capturing groups and avoiding nested quantifiers mitigates this.\n\n### False positives on agent-generated briefs discussing injection\nThis very brief — which discusses prompt injection patterns extensively — would likely trigger multiple scanner patterns if scanned. The benign corpus fixtures must include content that *discusses* injection (meta-content) to prevent this. The brief explicitly calls this out, but it's worth emphasizing: the test fixtures ARE the regression guard.\n\n### WritDoc injectionScan field visible to agents\nThe `injectionScan` field on WritDoc will be visible to any code reading writs — including agents via `writ-show`. This means an agent can see whether a writ was flagged. This is intentional (the brief says downstream tooling should display warnings) but worth noting: a sophisticated attacker who can read the writ could learn which patterns were detected and adjust their approach."
}

