"observations": "# Observations\n\n## Refactoring opportunities skipped\n\n- **Tool handler caller identity.** Tool handlers (`commission-post.ts`, `writ-edit.ts`) have no way to know who called them at runtime. The `callableBy` field on `ToolDefinition` is a registration-time gate, not runtime context. The `tool-server.ts` knows about session auth (patron vs. anima) but does not propagate caller type to handlers. This is fine for the current brief (D1 resolves the trust boundary architecturally by placing scanning in the tool handler layer), but future features that need per-caller behavior in tool handlers will hit this gap. A runtime caller context parameter on tool handlers would be a useful framework-level enhancement — separate commission.\n\n- **`PostCommissionRequest` growing.** Adding `injectionScan` to the request type (D2) makes it the fourth optional field after `type`, `codex`, and `draft`. If more metadata fields accrue (audit info, source tracking, etc.), consider a separate `metadata` bag rather than widening the request interface. Not worth doing now for one field.\n\n## Suboptimal conventions followed for consistency\n\n- **console.warn for CLI feedback (D6).** Using `console.warn()` in a tool handler to produce CLI stderr output is pragmatic but mixes concerns — tool handlers should ideally be environment-agnostic. The codebase already uses `console.warn()` in clerk.ts (kit registration warnings, line 141-143, 152-154) and instrumentarium.ts (instructions file load failures, line 225-227), so this is consistent with existing practice. A proper structured warning/diagnostic channel in the tool framework would be cleaner, but that's a framework enhancement.\n\n- **Scanning in tool handlers, not clerk API.** This means any future patron-entry surface (HTTP webhook, delegated posting agent) will need its own scanning integration — copy the same pattern from the tool handlers. The brief acknowledges this: \"so other surfaces (future HTTP intake, future delegated-posting agents) can reuse [the scanner] without an apparatus dependency.\" The scanner module's standalone importability is the mitigation.\n\n## Doc/code discrepancies (from inventory)\n\n- **`summon` as built-in type.** Both `packages/plugins/clerk/README.md` (line 61) and `docs/architecture/apparatus/clerk.md` (line 219) claim `summon` is a built-in type alongside `mandate`. Code (`clerk.ts` line 58: `const BUILTIN_TYPES = new Set(['mandate'])`) and tests (line 1268-1273) confirm only `mandate` is built-in. These docs are stale.\n\n- **Brief uses \"writ-post\" for a tool that doesn't exist.** The brief references \"Clerk `writ-post` tool\" in section 3.2, but the actual tool name is `commission-post`. The brief's reference section correctly points to `commission-post.ts`. The implementation should follow the actual tool name, not the brief's shorthand.\n\n## Potential risks\n\n- **False-positive risk on agent self-description.** The brief itself is an example of content that discusses prompt injection patterns extensively — if a commission body quotes injection patterns (as teaching material, security documentation, or meta-discussion), the scanner must not false-positive. The brief's benign-corpus test fixtures (8-12 fixtures including \"ones that *discuss* prompt injection, that reference system prompts in quoted form, that contain code blocks with role-looking strings\") are the primary mitigation. Pattern authors should err toward narrow high-confidence patterns rather than broad catches.\n\n- **`injectionScan` field indexing.** The `injectionScan` field on WritDoc is nested and not indexed in Stacks. If downstream tooling (oculus dashboard, reviewer agents) needs to query for flagged writs, a Stacks index on `injectionScan.clean` or a top-level boolean field would be needed. Not in scope for this brief, but worth noting if the audit trail becomes query-heavy.\n\n- **Performance test environment sensitivity.** The brief requires \"<10ms for 10kB body\" confirmed by a test. CI runners vary in speed. The test should use a generous margin (e.g., assert < 50ms) or run multiple iterations and check the median, rather than a hard 10ms assert that will flake on slow CI.\n\n## Package.json changes needed\n\n- The `exports` field in `packages/plugins/clerk/package.json` currently has only `\".\"`. Adding the subpath export `\"./scanner\"` (D3) requires updating both `exports` (dev path) and `publishConfig.exports` (built path). The `files` array may also need to include the scanner's built output if it's not already covered by `\"dist\"`.\n"

