endpoint (e.g., `/healthz` or an equivalent the clerk apparatus already exposes).\" There is no `/healthz` and no clerk-exposed health endpoint. D7 recommends adding `/healthz` to the tool server. The clerk apparatus is not involved.\n\n## Risks\n\n- **Health probe timeout.** If the tool server is hung (not dead, just unresponsive), the health probe could block the Spider's crawl loop. The spec should mandate a short timeout (e.g., 2–5 seconds) on the HTTP fetch to `/healthz` so the probe fails fast rather than hanging the crawl.\n\n- **Race between tool-server startup and first engine run.** If a rig is dispatched before the tool server is fully listening, health probes will fail spuriously. The current codebase starts the tool server during apparatus `start()`, which completes before the Spider processes rigs — so this should not be an issue in practice. But if the startup order ever changes, this could cause false precondition failures.\n\n## Adjacent work\n\n- **Sibling quest `w-mnt3r8al` (tool-call trace-based completion check)** is complementary — precondition checks prevent launching against dead services, trace checks verify the session actually did its work. The two defenses compose: precondition catches infrastructure failures, trace catches model-level no-ops. No coordination needed between the two implementations.\n\n- **Session output salvage.** The source quest notes that the failed reader session produced a correct inventory in its prose output but couldn't write it via MCP. Salvaging prose outputs from failed sessions is explicitly out of scope per the brief, but remains a valuable follow-up — the 7.5 minutes of reader work was correct, just unrecoverable."
